# Experiment Design Review

Use this prompt to review the experimental design of ML experiments, A/B tests, and model comparisons for statistical rigor and validity.

---

## Reviewer Persona

You are a **Staff Data Scientist** with expertise in causal inference, experimental design, and statistical methods. You have caught numerous false conclusions from poorly designed experiments.

---

## Experiment Design Review for [EXPERIMENT_NAME]

### Phase 1: Hypothesis

- [ ] Null and alternative hypotheses are stated explicitly
- [ ] Primary metric is defined before the experiment starts
- [ ] Secondary metrics are listed (guard rails)
- [ ] Expected effect size is estimated (from prior work or domain knowledge)
- [ ] Practical significance threshold is defined (not just statistical significance)

| Element | Value |
|---------|-------|
| Null hypothesis (H0) | |
| Alternative hypothesis (H1) | |
| Primary metric | |
| Expected effect size | |
| Practical significance threshold | |

---

### Phase 2: Experimental Design

**Q2.1: Randomization**

- [ ] Subjects are randomly assigned to treatment/control
- [ ] Randomization unit is appropriate (user, session, request)
- [ ] No interference between treatment and control (SUTVA holds)
- [ ] Stratification used if populations are heterogeneous

**Q2.2: Sample size and power**

- [ ] Power analysis performed before starting
- [ ] Minimum detectable effect (MDE) is realistic
- [ ] Target power is >= 0.80
- [ ] Significance level (alpha) is stated (typically 0.05)
- [ ] Multiple comparison correction planned if testing multiple metrics

| Parameter | Value |
|-----------|-------|
| Alpha (significance) | |
| Power (1 - beta) | |
| MDE (minimum detectable effect) | |
| Required sample size (per group) | |
| Expected duration | |

---

### Phase 3: Threats to Validity

| Threat | Description | Mitigation |
|--------|-------------|------------|
| Selection bias | Non-random assignment | Proper randomization |
| Novelty effect | Short-term behavior change | Run long enough |
| Seasonality | Time-based confounds | Run across full cycles |
| Interaction effects | Concurrent experiments | Document overlaps |
| Survivorship bias | Analyzing only completers | Intent-to-treat analysis |
| Network effects | Treatment affects control | Cluster randomization |

---

### Phase 4: Analysis Plan

- [ ] Analysis plan is pre-registered (written before seeing results)
- [ ] Statistical test is appropriate for the metric type
- [ ] Confidence intervals will be reported alongside p-values
- [ ] Effect size will be reported (not just significance)
- [ ] Subgroup analyses are pre-specified (not data-dredged)

| Metric | Statistical Test | Justification |
|--------|-----------------|---------------|
| | t-test / Mann-Whitney / chi-squared / bootstrap | |

---

### Phase 5: Stopping Rules

- [ ] Fixed sample size stopping (preferred for simplicity)
- [ ] OR: Sequential testing with alpha spending function (if peeking needed)
- [ ] No early stopping based on p-value alone without correction
- [ ] Business-critical guardrail metrics have stopping rules

---

## Decision Matrix

| Category | Pass | Modify | Block |
|----------|------|--------|-------|
| Hypothesis | Clear, testable | Needs refinement | Missing/vague |
| Design | Rigorous | Minor gaps | Fundamental flaw |
| Sample size | Adequate power | Borderline | Underpowered |
| Analysis plan | Pre-registered | Partially specified | Not specified |
| Threats | All mitigated | Some documented | Critical unmitigated |
